  <h1 class="hidetitle">The Important Decisions Document</h1> 
  <h2>Every project (and family) needs one.</h2> 
  <h3>Thomas A. Limoncelli</h3> 
  <p>Long-running projects are a journey. An IDD (important decisions doc) captures knowledge and decisions gathered along the way. It records the what and why of decisions, as well as the rationale for rejecting alternatives. It helps new team members get up to speed, prevents wasting time on relitigating old decisions, improves morale, and increases accountability.</p> 
  <p>The important decision doc (IDD) is a tool used at Stack Overflow during long-running projects. It is a living document that records major decisions made by the people directly involved. It is constructed over time during the execution phase of a project—unlike specification documents or project proposals, which are created beforehand (if they are created at all).</p> 
  <p>The IDD becomes a resource that provides clarity. It helps new project members get up to speed quickly. Existing document members can use it as a reference. It gives team members a healthy way to raise and resolve issues while also holding decisionmakers accountable. It’s lightweight and easy to use.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>The Meeting that Started it All</h3>
  <p>I had joined the project only a week prior. Others had been involved for many months. The first time I attended the weekly status meeting I learned that a particular technology had been selected for the project’s next phase.</p> 
  <p>“Why?” I asked innocently. This completely derailed the meeting. Oops.</p> 
  <p>People on the losing side of the decision took this as an opportunity to vent about why it was a bad decision and rally for their preferred solution. Soon the decision was being relitigated. The rest of the meeting was consumed by the debate. By the time the meeting ended, we had arrived again at the same conclusion. We were back where we started.</p> 
  <p>As the meeting came to a close, someone shared his frustration about how this wasn’t the first time this had happened. There had to be a better way!</p> 
  <p>It turns out this pattern of revisiting and rearguing past decisions seemed to happen every time a new person joined the project, or whenever a forgetful person asked to be reminded of a particular outcome. It also happened whenever a decision was made months before the decision was needed and, now that the issue had become ripe, leaving time to rehash differences of opinion.</p> 
  <p>Revisiting past decisions wasn’t just a waste of time. It was hurting morale. Habitually relitigated arguments are frustrating, especially when they rarely lead to changes. It just demoralizes the people who favored the decision, and deepens the frustration of those that disagreed.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>The Important Decisions Document</h3>
  <p>After this first meeting I attended, the team leader created a document called the Important Decisions Doc, which listed many of the key decisions that had been made. He also set up a series of meetings to review that document and, in his words, “re-decide those issues one last time.”</p> 
  <p>The meetings were a success. All sides got to have their say. Both pro and con arguments were recorded. Also documented were the “what” and the “why” of the decision. This not only settled long-standing issues, but also provided closure so we could move on.</p> 
  <p>New important decisions were added to the document over time. Project members were encouraged to address new issues using the IDD template, which then would be discussed and settled at the next meeting.</p> 
  <p>New people on the project could read the full document to get up to speed. Forgetful people could refer to it for answers instead of derailing meetings. Managers were held accountable for past decisions.</p> 
  <h4>The Format</h4>
  <p>Adding a new decision is lightweight. Simply copy the template and fill out the fields. The template is conveniently located at the bottom of the document.</p> 
  <p>The IDD format is intentionally simple, consisting of four core fields: Question, Options, Rationale, and Notes. The template, shown in figure 1, guides contributors to capture the full decision context. Figure 2 contains two examples.</p> 
  <br />
  <br /> 
