  <div id="T2"> 
   <table frame="hsides" rules="rows">
    <thead valign="bottom">
     <tr>
      <th align="left" valign="top" colspan="2"><p>1. <span style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:1.5em;">☑</span> Test environments should be identical to production</p> </th>
     </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
     <tr> 
      <td align="left" valign="top"><p><b>Question</b></p> </td> 
      <td align="left" valign="top"><p>How should we build test environments?</p> </td>
     </tr>
     <tr> 
      <td align="left" valign="top"><p><b>Options</b></p> </td> 
      <td align="left" valign="top"><p>• These should be identical to production, except for scale and access levels, with test environments being more permissive.</p> <p>   ○ We will have no shared dependencies between test and production environments.</p> <p>   ○ We will strive to keep network routing as similar as possible (e.g., deviation: test environments blocking public access).</p> <p>   ○ At least one test environment will have a DR region configured in the same way as production, for testing replication and failover.</p> <p>   ○ Application configuration will be as similar as possible (e.g., deviation: New feature flag enabled in test environment before production).</p> <p>   ○ We will use prebuilt application artifacts and IaC (Infrastructure as Code) to follow a “build once, deploy many” model.</p> </td>
     </tr>
     <tr> 
      <td align="left" valign="top"><p><b>Rationale</b></p> </td> 
      <td align="left" valign="top"><p>In the data center we have been limited based on physical hardware to deploy test environments. This has led us to have very different configurations for our test environments. These differences have caused inconsistent testing results, engineers testing in production, and production outages.</p> <br /> <p>We can leverage IaC to deploy identical test environments to ensure consistent results between test and production. Resource allocation can be scaled down in the test environments to reduce waste.</p> </td>
     </tr>
     <tr> 
      <td align="left" valign="top"><p><b>Notes</b></p> </td> 
     </tr>
    </tbody>
   </table> 
  </div> 
  <br />
  <br /> 
  <p>Above the box appears a numbered heading that lists a title for the decision, which should be a declarative statement of the final decision. Once a decision is complete, a checkbox emoji is added.</p> 
  <p>People then are given an opportunity to insert their own options, refine existing ones, or add comments and questions. Here, the use of word-processing software that provides for real-time collaborative editing, such as Google Docs, is essential.</p> 
  <p>The final decision then is made at a meeting with all stakeholders in attendance. This is generally done as part of weekly status meetings, although special meetings can be set up to bootstrap the system or if one or more new decisions require extended discussion. The preference is for live (virtual or in-person) meetings for these discussions. While email and chatrooms are excellent for some things, I believe high-bandwidth communication is best for this kind of discussion. People collaborate better when they can see each other’s faces. Text cannot convey emotion as immediately or effectively.</p> 
  <p>Then, as the discussion progresses, options are eliminated. Those are never deleted, but the text font is changed to strike-out. This way information is preserved for historical purposes, to educate new members on context and to provide for those instances where rejected options will need to be revisited. More importantly, it is essential that individuals who disagreed with the final decision feel their concerns were heard and noted.</p> 
  <p>Once a final decision is made, that option is highlighted in bold.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Use Cases</h4>
  <p>IDD is useful for many kinds of decisions. It allows a controversial decision to be made transparently. A contentious decision becomes less heated when everyone sees all the options and learns about everyone’s concerns. People are more willing to accept someone else’s proposal if their own concerns are recorded. The group builds trust as they collaboratively decide which options are unworkable, and then uses that trust to pick from the remaining issues.</p> 
  <p>Sometimes the decisions are more technical than controversial. For example, one team had to decide which Google Cloud region to use for a new application. The IDD listed all the potential regions plus a list of requirements such as size and capabilities. The IDD meeting was less of a debate about which option to pick than it was an exercise in documenting why regions were eliminated. Eventually there was only one region remaining, and everyone let out a big sigh of relief that the number of remaining regions wasn’t zero. Later, when someone wanted to know why the “west” cluster of this application was not so geographically western, the IDD provided a record of how that decision had been made.</p> 
  <p>Some decisions require more background and analysis than can fit in a box. For those, the options section links to an external doc. Still, in addition to that, the options are summarized in the IDD for easy reference.</p> 
  <p>Other decisions are purely a record of fact or a statement of direction. For example, one IDD simply clarified the definition of certain terms. Another conveyed that the team agreed to adopt a particular policy related to how a certain recurring issue would be handled in the future. Another recorded the division of labor (who would do what) between two sub-teams.</p> 
  <p>While some of these examples may appear unimportant, I assure you that the clarity provided by explicitly documenting these decisions proved valuable.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Tips</h4>
  <p>It should be easy to add new questions to the IDD. If someone feels something is important enough to be listed, it should be listed and given consideration. Do not create a bureaucratic barrier to entry.</p> 
  <p>Decisions need to “stick.” Therefore, decisions need buy-in from all appropriate stakeholders. For example, if a decision will affect resource allocation (i.e., budgets), then the owner of the budget in question should be involved. Likewise if a decision requires enforcement by a particular manager. Identifying those stakeholders may be a challenge.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Priming the Pump</h4>
  <p>The IDD was such a success for one project that other projects adopted the format.</p> 
  <p>One smart technical project manager used IDD as a way to kick off a major project. He began the project with a series of meetings to get agreement on more than a dozen IDD questions. They ranged from controversial decisions to those that were needed early to unblock long-lead items to simple issues that just needed to be recorded.</p> 
  <p>These marathon meetings not only clarified many issues, but also helped the newly formed team work through Tuckman’s stages of group development (Forming, Storming, Norming, and so on).</p> 
  <p>Some of the issues needed buy-in from people who would not normally be in attendance (i.e., sales and customer support). Those issues were split out to a separate series of meetings so those additional stakeholders could attend. They appreciated being involved so early, and this reduced the number of surprises at the end of the project. It was also more time efficient than having those particular stakeholders at the main meeting, bored to death waiting for an IDD that concerned them.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Benefits</h4>
  <p>The goal of the IDD is to eliminate wasted engineering time caused by relitigating past decisions. It succeeded in this regard, and we gained the following direct benefits:</p> 
  <p>• Project velocity was enhanced by having fewer repeated discussions.</p> 
  <p>• Decisions “stuck” better because they were recorded.</p> 
  <p>• People felt better about their option being rejected when they felt heard.</p> 
  <p>• Onboarding new team members was accelerated.</p> 
  <p>• Managers were held accountable for past decisions.</p> 
  <p>There also were some unexpected benefits.</p> 
  <p>• Employee morale improved. Nothing kills morale like having to sit through the same debate over and over. Engineers value stability and efficiency.</p> 
  <p>• It also improved the relationship between everyone involved. Language can be imprecise. Having the opportunity to record clarifications and examples in the document improves people’s ability to know what they’re agreeing to, and this minimizes future confusion.</p> 
  <p>“Yes” can mean agreement or acknowledgment that the previous statement was heard. IDD becomes a forcing function that prevents “I heard you” from being misinterpreted as: “This is a decision I will uphold forever.” It reduces engineering mistrust of management when both parties have an IDD entry to refer to. Directors can no longer gaslight team members when forced to record a decision.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Life’s IDD</h3>
  <p>An IDD can be useful outside of work as well. The format is different, and certainly less formal, but equally as valuable.</p> 
  <p>On a personal level, I’ve found it useful to record certain important decisions in my personal journal. Did I rewire my house using Cat 6a or Cat 8 wire? I’m pretty sure I won’t remember a year from now. And that decision to try to stop convincing my brother-in-law about... well, exactly what doesn’t matter. Recording these decisions in my personal journal prevents me from revisiting those issues so I can spend more time thinking about more interesting things.</p> 
  <p>At the family level, an IDD can help avoid confusion, prevent disagreements, and facilitate domestic tranquility. It’s a game the whole family can play—although I don’t recommend using the template in figure 1 with your family unless they are all engineers. Keep it informal and fun.</p> 
  <p>I like to record near-term decisions on a whiteboard in the kitchen, and longer-term issues in a shared Google Doc. The whiteboard announces where we’re going on vacation this summer. The Google Doc records that we’ve all agreed not to replace the dishwasher until 2027 and that I agree to stop whining about it until then.</p> 
  <p>Maintaining a relationship certainly involves many decisions. That’s why we create and preserve written relationship agreements, wedding vows, budgets, and communication agreements.</p> 
  <p>We also record important decisions for when we are no longer around, such as wills, living trusts, power of attorney, and other end-of-life documents. (Let this serve as a reminder to update yours).</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Conclusion</h3>
  <p>Long-running projects are a journey. An IDD captures knowledge and decisions gathered along the way. It records the what and why of decisions, as well as the rationale for rejecting alternatives. It helps new team members get up to speed, prevents wasting time on relitigating old decisions, improves morale, and increases accountability.</p> 
  <p>Using a template improves consistency and becomes a guide for team members who want to contribute. Something less formal is better for personal IDDs, however.</p> 
  <p>No requirements document or project plan can predict all the twists and turns of a multimonth project. Most of the decisions in a project are made along the way. An IDD captures these decisions in a collaborative and transparent way.</p> 
  <p>The IDD is not just a document; it is a vital process that codifies agreement, prevents process churn, and preserves precious engineering focus.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
